# .rules

## General Project Rules

- This is a static GitHub Pages project.
- Keep everything simple, readable, and maintainable.
- Prefer HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Bootstrap.
- Do not introduce backend.
- Do not add database.
- Do not add login/register.
- Do not add build tools.
- Do not require `npm install`.
- Do not break existing pages.
- Do not change existing URLs unless explicitly requested.

## Course Creation Rules

When the user asks to create a course, the AI must:

1. Create course folder.
2. Create course overview page.
3. Split theory content into suitable lessons.
4. Create lesson pages.
5. Create sidebar or table of contents.
6. Create quiz JavaScript.
7. Create essay self-study section.
8. Create suggested answers.
9. Add previous/next lesson navigation.
10. Update `index.html` with the new course.
11. Update `courses.html` if it exists.
12. Ensure responsive layout for mobile, tablet, laptop, and desktop.

## Do Not Stop At Text

When creating or refactoring a course, do not only write course content in the chat.

The AI must create or modify project files.

## Required Lesson Sections

Every lesson must include:

```txt
Video mô phỏng
Tài liệu lý thuyết
Ví dụ minh họa
Bài tập thực hành
Trắc nghiệm
Câu hỏi tự luận
Đáp án tham khảo
```

## Educational Quality Rule

A lesson is incomplete if:

- Theory is too short.
- Theory is generic.
- Examples are missing.
- Examples are not explained.
- Code has no comments.
- Common mistakes are missing.
- Practice exercises are missing.

The goal is to teach a beginner successfully, not merely create HTML pages.

## Theory Must Be Detailed

Reject:

- Generic explanation
- One-paragraph explanation
- Shallow definitions
- Content that only lists syntax without explanation

Require every important concept to include:

1. Definition
2. Why it is needed
3. When to use it
4. Syntax
5. How it works step by step
6. Practical example
7. Common mistakes
8. Short summary

## Programming Lesson Rules

For programming courses, each lesson must include at least:

- 2 complete runnable programs
- 1 basic example
- 1 practical example

Each program must contain:

- `#include`
- `main()`
- input/output if relevant
- Vietnamese comments
- expected output if possible

Do not use isolated snippets as the only example.

Bad example:

```cpp
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

Good example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    // Trả về tổng của hai số nguyên
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    // Khai báo hai biến số nguyên
    int x = 5;
    int y = 3;

    // Gọi hàm add để tính tổng
    int result = add(x, y);

    // In kết quả ra màn hình
    cout << "Tong la: " << result;

    return 0;
}
```

## Code Comment Rules

All code examples must contain comments.

Minimum requirement:

- 1 comment per logical block
- Comment before important operations
- Comment for variables that may confuse beginners
- Comment for input/output logic
- Comment for loops, conditions, functions, pointers, arrays, structs, and files

Do not generate uncommented code for beginner lessons.

## Code Explanation Rules

After every code example, include a section named:

```txt
Giải thích chương trình
```

This section must explain:

- Program purpose
- Input
- Output
- Main variables
- Execution flow
- Important lines of code
- Expected result

## Inline Code Formatting Rules

Programming syntax must be wrapped with backticks when written in Markdown or converted into `<code>` when written in HTML.

Examples:

```txt
`int`
`float`
`double`
`char`
`bool`
`if`
`else`
`for`
`while`
`do-while`
`break`
`continue`
`cin`
`cout`
`return`
`struct`
`string`
`fstream`
`==`
`!=`
`<`
`>`
`<=`
`>=`
```

Never render programming keywords, operators, function names, or variable names as plain text when they are being explained.

## HTML Operator Escaping Rules

When generating raw HTML, escape comparison operators:

```txt
<  -> &lt;
>  -> &gt;
<= -> &lt;=
>= -> &gt;=
```

Do not output raw `<` or `>` directly in HTML text content because the browser may interpret them as tags.

Correct:

```html
<code>&lt;</code>
<code>&gt;</code>
<code>&lt;=</code>
<code>&gt;=</code>
```

Incorrect:

```html
<code><</code>
<code>></code>
```

## Practice Exercise Rules

Every lesson must include practice exercises.

Minimum:

```txt
3 easy exercises
2 medium exercises
```

For programming lessons, exercises should be practical and code-oriented.

Avoid only theoretical exercises.

## Quiz Rules

- Use JavaScript.
- Show score immediately.
- Do not send data to a server.
- Do not require account.
- Minimum 5 questions per lesson.

Quiz questions should include:

- Concept questions
- Syntax questions
- Output prediction questions
- Error detection questions
- Practical usage questions

Avoid only definition-based questions.

## Essay Rules

- Essay questions are self-study only.
- Do not grade essays.
- Suggested answer must be available.
- Suggested answer should be hidden by default.
- Learners can compare their answer manually.
- Minimum 2 essay questions per lesson.

Essay questions should encourage:

- Explanation
- Comparison
- Reasoning
- Reflection on how to apply the concept

Avoid yes/no questions.

## Homepage Rules

When adding a course, update `index.html`.

If `index.html` has a course section, add the new course there.

If `index.html` does not have a course section, create a course section.

The new course entry must link to:

```txt
courses/<course-slug>/index.html
```

If the homepage has agent markers, insert the course card between:

```txt
AGENT_COURSE_CARDS_START
AGENT_COURSE_CARDS_END
```

## Courses Page Rules

If `courses.html` exists, add the new course there.

If the page has agent markers, insert the course card between:

```txt
AGENT_COURSES_PAGE_CARDS_START
AGENT_COURSES_PAGE_CARDS_END
```

## Navigation Rules

Every course must include navigation.

Course overview page:

- Link to homepage
- Link to lessons
- Link to courses page if available

Lesson page:

- Link to homepage
- Link to course overview
- Link to all lessons in sidebar
- Link to previous lesson
- Link to next lesson

## Sidebar Rules

Every lesson page must include a sidebar or table of contents.

Desktop/laptop:

- Sidebar on the left
- Lesson content on the right

Mobile:

- Sidebar above the content or collapsible
- No horizontal scrolling
- Buttons must be easy to tap

## Responsive Rules

Use Bootstrap responsive classes.

Required layout pattern:

```html
<main class="container my-4">
  <div class="row">
    <aside class="col-12 col-lg-3 mb-4">
      Sidebar
    </aside>

    <article class="col-12 col-lg-9">
      Lesson content
    </article>
  </div>
</main>
```

All pages must work on:

- Mobile
- Tablet
- Laptop
- Desktop

## Content Rules

- User-facing content should be Vietnamese.
- File and folder names should be English.
- Explain concepts clearly.
- Use beginner-friendly examples.
- Avoid overly long paragraphs.
- Use lists and tables where helpful.
- Use real programming examples for programming courses.
- Do not assume learners already know programming.

## C++ Course Rules

For C++ lessons, examples must be written in standard C++.

Use:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
```

when appropriate for beginner lessons.

For advanced lessons, include required libraries such as:

```cpp
#include <iomanip>
#include <string>
#include <fstream>
```

when needed.

Important C++ topics such as:

- functions
- pointers
- arrays
- strings
- structs
- files

must be explained in extra detail because they are foundations for Data Structures and Algorithms.

## Git Course Rules

For Git lessons, examples must include:

- Terminal commands
- Explanation of each command
- Expected output when useful
- Common mistakes
- Real workflow

Example:

```bash
git status
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

After each command block, explain:

- What the command does
- When to use it
- What result to expect
- Common error if any

## File Naming Rules

Use lowercase and hyphenated names.

Good examples:

```txt
agent-engineering
python-fundamentals
data-structures
lesson-01.html
binary-search.html
what-is-ai-agent.html
```

Bad examples:

```txt
Agent Engineering
Bai 1.html
Lesson 01.html
finalVersion.html
```

## Path Rules

Use relative paths.

Do not use local absolute paths like:

```txt
C:\Users\...
/home/user/...
```

Do not use root-relative paths like:

```txt
/assets/css/style.css
```

unless the project is specifically configured for that.

## CSS Rules

Global style should be placed in:

```txt
assets/css/style.css
```

Course-specific style should be placed in:

```txt
assets/css/course.css
```

Inline CSS should be avoided unless very small.

Inline code elements should be visually highlighted using CSS for `code`.

## JavaScript Rules

Global JavaScript should be placed in:

```txt
assets/js/main.js
```

Quiz JavaScript should be placed in:

```txt
assets/js/quiz.js
```

Lesson-specific JavaScript should be placed in:

```txt
assets/js/lesson.js
```

Avoid duplicating large JavaScript blocks across many lesson pages if reusable logic already exists.

## Safety Rules

- Do not store API keys.
- Do not store passwords.
- Do not include private user data.
- Do not use external paid services by default.
- Do not track learners.
- Do not send quiz or essay data to any server.

## Final Output Rules

After creating or refactoring a course, summarize:

```txt
Created:
- ...

Modified:
- ...

Improved:
- ...

Notes:
- ...
```

Always mention whether:

- Course folder was created
- Lesson pages were created or updated
- Sidebar was added or updated
- Quiz was added or updated
- Essay section was added or updated
- `index.html` was updated
- `courses.html` was updated